ious Cleric thread, but since it's more of a debate topic and that thread is a general description topic, I decided to make it a seperate thread. A great deal of this will apply to all classes, as DAoC characters are class/skill driven rather than just class driven.<br>
<br>
Clerics, like the other classes, can take a variety of forms. Some things every cleric will have in common. <br>
<br>
They may be using a mace or a hammer, but their melee skills will be roughly equal regardless. Are they the &quot;equal&quot; of an Armsman? In melee damage over time, no, they are not. They are, however, effective melee fighters none the less. At level 22, my beta cleric actually did *more* damage per hit than some of the Paladins I grouped with (the ones using 1h weapons). The Paladin's styles added different things that I could not add (damage, taunt, etc) but straight up whacking, my hammer outdamaged their sword every time. So, while not the best, don't discount the cleric's melee skills. Late in a fight and out of power, I have seen the cleric's melee skills turn defeat into victory more than once (yes, this is a last ditch effort when running is not an option or when another rezer has already cleared the area and is safe).<br>
<br>
Another commonality is protection. Clerics get nothing better than chainmail armor, which is the third best available (I believe scaled and plate are both superior). They also have medium shields available to them. Like melee, the shield skill is not trainable so they get no shield styles. They are, however, quite adept at blocking. Again, can they stand in like an Armsman? No way. Clerics will take the same damage as the chainmailed Armsman, but the Armsman will have far more hit points to give and thus much better durability when being hit. Thus, clerics are not fragile finger wagglers, but niether are they tanks. Put them in the category of &quot;It's okay to take a few hits, but either kill it quick or taunt it off fairly soon or things will start to get ugly.&quot;<br>
<br>
Having established that clerics are not fragile and are mediocre meleers, we get to the meat of the class, and the factor that differentiates one cleric from another. Their magical abilities.<br>
<br>
Here is where the cleric you just invited to your group becomes an unknown. There are two basic types, and literally dozens of permutations on those types.<br>
<br>
The Healing Cleric. The healing cleric is speced in Rejuvination, with strong Enhancement skills as well. He has the best and most varied selection of heals available in the realm (and the game, actually.. clerics surpass Druids and Healers in this capacity). Typically, if he's an accomplished healer, he will start healing early in the fight using low level heals to stay ahead of the damage being taken. If things get a little rough it's no problem. Throughout his development, the healing cleric gains progressively more potent abilities that allow him to heal an Armsman of a similar level from near death to well over half health in a single shot. He also has group heals of various levels, which are useful during 'furballs'. In short, the healing cleric is very capable of keeping you healthy in even the hardest fight, so long as it doesn't drag out too long. In this respect, if in no other, the DAoC cleric is comparable to the EQ cleric. A good healing cleric will stand at the start of the fight and remain well back from the melee group. He will heal until he's out of power, then make his decision whether to run, fight or sit. <br>
<br>
The healing cleric also has some offensive casting ability. Even with only minimal training, the offensive abilities gained through leveling keep the healing cleric able to deal effective damage through casting, though nowhere near the damage a pure caster can dish out. Additionally, he will have stuns and his instant cast, AE mez ability.<br>
<br>
The Smiting Cleric. This is a different animal altogether from the healing cleric. The smiting cleric has put most of his training into his offensive skills. The Smite speced cleric has damage casting abilities only slightly inferior to a well-speced Wizard, but with the melee and armor skills described earlier. He also has a variety of damage lines to choose from based on the situation, with all of them vastly superior to a healing cleric's. It's been said that a smite cleric is the most powerful solo class in the realm because of this unique mix of powerful magic and average melee abilities. In a group, the smite cleric is nowhere near the healer that a healing cleric is. Instead, he adds potent offense to the group, with an ability to heal that is virtually the same as the Friar's. A skilled smiting cleric will not try to tank for the group, but niether will he hold back on his damage output for fear of agro the way a good caster will. From what I've seen, a good smite cleric will step into the mix at the start of the fight and use his mez to freeze adds. He will then step back and begin casting damage spells. If he draws agro or runs out of power he will step back in and melee, running only if no other rezer has been able to move a safe distance away.<br>
<br>
Does this mean avoid grouping with smiting clerics? Absolutely not! It does mean find out up front what you're getting when you group a cleric. Are you adding offensive or defensive abilities to your group? Don't make the mistake of thinking you can put a smite cleric into the role of primary group healer and he will be as effective as a healing cleric. He won't. He's an offensive fighter, not a healer. If you must use a smite cleric as your main healer simply look at it as though you have a Friar as your main healer. He can do it, but like the Friar, it's not what he does best.<br>
<br>
Dog<br>
